Activity: A17 - Discover 10 different types of locks in use

Objective
The goal of this activity was to identify and analyse different types of locks used to secure physical and digital assets in everyday environments.

Method
I observed locks used at home, school, and public places and also researched different locking mechanisms to understand how they function and where they are commonly used.

Findings
The following types of locks were identified:
1. Password/PIN lock - traditional device login method
2. Biometric lock - uses unique biological traits
3. Two-factor authentication codes - adds extra step using devices or apps
4. Hardware token / key fob - generates one-time passwords for secure logins
5. Smart lock - controlled digitally, often with encryption
6. Keycard / RFID access - digital card access for restricted areas
7. magnetic lock integrated with network systems - access controlled via digital credentials 
8. Encryption USB drive / secure storage device - requires authentication to access sensitive files
9. Secure software vault / password manager - digital "lock" to manage credentials safety
10. Screen lock timeout / auto-lock feature - automatically locks devices after inactivty to prevent unauthorised access

Security Principle
These digital locks demonstrate authentication and access control, which are essential for confidentiality and integrity of data in cybersecurity

Evidence
- photos in evidence folder

Reflection
This activity helped me realise that access control is more than just a physical lock - in cybersecurity, the principle of "who can access what" is applied everywhere, from your phone to cloud storage to smart school systems. understanding these mechanisms is key to protecting sensitive digital assets
